                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 143.—<name type="person" key="683">Private James
                                                Loveland</name>, <name type="organization" key="197">Co. G, 4th Vt.</name>, was admitted <date type="admit" when="1863-11-23">Nov. 23, 1863</date>,
                                                <date type="death" when="1863-11-23">moribund</date>.  <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi>
                                        examination: Toes and anterior portion of metatarsus of both
                                        feet gangrenous.  [<hi rend="italic">Specimens</hi> 79 and
                                        80, Med. Sect., <name type="hospital" key="431">Army Medical
                                                Museum</name>, constitute the only record: 79, a
                                        portion of the upper part of the ileum, shows a single
                                        oblong and thickened Peyer's patch; 80, a portion of the
                                        lower part, presents two thickened and ulcerated patches and
                                        two small ulcers, corresponding probably to solitary
                                                follicles.]—<hi rend="italic"><name type="person" key="200">Ass't Surg. W.
                                                  Thomson</name>, <name type="organization" key="190">U. S. A.</name>, <name type="hospital" key="162">Douglas Hospital</name>, Washington, D. C.</hi></p>                        
